│ ### 1. Analysis of the Crash                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The crash occurs when running `opt` with `-passes=loop-vectorize`.                                                           │
│ The error message is: `PHINode should have one entry for each predecessor of its parent basic block! %use = phi i64 [        │
│ %start2, %for.body ]`.                                                                                                       │
│ This indicates that the `loop-vectorize` pass is creating malformed IR. The PHI node `%use` in the `exit` block becomes      │
│ invalid.                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The PHI node `%use` is defined as `phi i64 [ %start2, %for.body ]`. Its parent block is `exit`. In the original IR, `exit`   │
│ has only one predecessor, `for.body`, so the PHI is valid.                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The loop vectorizer transforms the loop. It creates a vectorized version of the loop and usually keeps the original loop as  │
│ a scalar epilogue. This process involves changing the control flow graph. A new block, the "vector loop exit block", is      │
│ created, which also branches to the original loop's exit block (`exit`). This means the `exit` block gets a new predecessor. │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The problem is that the PHI node `%use` is not updated to include an incoming value for this new predecessor. The PHI node   │
│ `%use` uses `%start2`, which is defined outside the loop. The loop vectorizer has logic to handle values defined outside the │
│ loop that are used inside the loop (called "loop-invariant values"). However, it seems to be missing logic for               │
│ loop-invariant values that are used *after* the loop, in a PHI node in the loop's exit block.                                │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ### 2. Locating the Relevant Code                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The crash happens within the `LoopVectorizePass`. The core logic for vectorization is in `LoopVectorizePass::processLoop`    │
│ and the `LoopVectorizationLegality` and `InnerLoopVectorizer` classes it uses. The file                                      │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp` is the main place to look.                                                 │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The process of creating the vectorized loop and epilogue involves creating new basic blocks and adjusting control flow. The  │
│ PHI nodes in the exit block need to be updated. This is typically done by `InnerLoopVectorizer::fixupIVUsers`. This function │
│ iterates over the users of the induction variable and other loop-related values.                                             │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The PHI node `%use` is not directly related to the induction variable. It uses a loop-invariant value `%start2`. The         │
│ vectorizer has a mechanism to handle such values. It seems this mechanism is incomplete.                                     │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ### 3. Devising a Fix                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The fix should ensure that any PHI node in the loop's exit block is correctly updated when the vectorizer adds a new         │
│ predecessor to it.                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The `InnerLoopVectorizer::fixupIVUsers` function seems like a good place to add this logic. It already deals with updating   │
│ PHI nodes for induction variables. We can extend it to handle PHI nodes that use loop-invariant values.                      │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The logic should be:                                                                                                         │
│ 1.  Iterate through all PHI nodes in the loop's exit blocks.                                                                 │
│ 2.  For each PHI node, check if it's now invalid because it's missing an entry for the new predecessor (the vector loop's    │
│ exit block).                                                                                                                 │
│ 3.  If a PHI is missing an entry, determine the correct incoming value. Since the value used in the original PHI (`%start2`) │
│ is loop-invariant, the same value should be used for the incoming edge from the vectorized loop.                             │
│ 4.  Add the new incoming value and block to the PHI node.                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ Looking at `InnerLoopVectorizer::fixupIVUsers`, it iterates through `IVUsers` which are users of the induction variable. The │
│ problematic PHI `%use` is not a user of the induction variable. So we need to add a new loop.                                │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The function `InnerLoopVectorizer::fixupIVUsers` takes a `VectorParts` map, which contains the vectorized versions of        │
│ instructions. The new predecessor is `VectorLoopExitBB`.                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The proposed change is to add the following logic to `InnerLoopVectorizer::fixupIVUsers`:                                    │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                       │
│ // After fixing up users of the induction variable, fix up other PHIs                                                        │
│ // in the exit blocks.                                                                                                       │
│ for (BasicBlock *ExitBB : L->getExitBlocks()) {                                                                              │
│   for (PHINode &PN : ExitBB->phis()) {                                                                                       │
│     // If the PHI is already valid, we don't need to do anything.                                                            │
│     if (PN.getBasicBlockIndex(VectorLoopExitBB) != -1)                                                                       │
│       continue;                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                              │
│     // The PHI is invalid. We need to add an entry for VectorLoopExitBB.                                                     │
│     // The value should be the same as the one from the original loop preheader,                                             │
│     // as it must be a loop invariant.                                                                                       │
│     Value *V = PN.getIncomingValueForBlock(L->getLoopPreheader());                                                           │
│     PN.addIncoming(V, VectorLoopExitBB);                                                                                     │
│   }                                                                                                                          │
│ }                                                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                                                          │
│ This logic iterates through all exit blocks, then all PHIs in those blocks. If a PHI is missing an entry for                 │
│ `VectorLoopExitBB`, it adds one. It assumes the correct value to add is the one coming from the original loop's preheader,   │
│ which is correct for a loop-invariant value.                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The original loop's preheader is not directly available. However, the existing incoming block for the PHI (`for.body` in the │
│ reproducer) is dominated by the preheader, and the value (`%start2`) is defined before the loop. The existing incoming block │
│ for the PHI is the loop's latch (`for.body`). The value `%start2` is defined in `entry`, which is the preheader in this      │
│ case. The PHI `%use` has an incoming edge from `for.body`. The value is `%start2`. This is a bit strange. The value should   │
│ be from the preheader. Let's re-check the IR.                                                                                │
│ `%use = phi i64 [ %start2, %for.body ]`                                                                                      │
│ The predecessor of `exit` is `for.body`. This is correct.                                                                    │
│ The value `%start2` is defined in `entry`.                                                                                   │
│ The loop vectorizer will have `OrigPH` as the preheader. The latch is `for.body`.                                            │
│ The value `%start2` is available in the preheader.                                                                           │
│ The PHI `%use` has one incoming edge from the latch. The value is `%start2`. This is a loop invariant.                       │
│ When `VectorLoopExitBB` is added as a predecessor to `exit`, the PHI `%use` needs an incoming value from it. Since `%start2` │
│ is loop invariant, it's the correct value.                                                                                   │
│ The existing code in `fixupIVUsers` uses `OrigPH` (original preheader). The PHI `%use` doesn't have an incoming edge from    │
│ `OrigPH`. It has one from `for.body`.                                                                                        │
│ The value `%start2` is defined in `entry`. The loop header is `for.body`. The preheader is `entry`.                          │
│ The PHI `%use` is in `exit`. The predecessor of `exit` is `for.body`.                                                        │
│ The value `%start2` is available in `for.body`.                                                                              │
│ The logic `PN.getIncomingValueForBlock(L->getLoopPreheader())` will fail because there is no incoming edge from the          │
│ preheader to this PHI.                                                                                                       │
│ The value must be something that is live out of the vectorized loop and available in `VectorLoopExitBB`. For a loop          │
│ invariant, it's the value itself.                                                                                            │
│ We can just pick any incoming value of the PHI, as it must be a loop invariant.                                              │
│ So, `Value *V = PN.getIncomingValue(0);` should work.                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ Let's implement this fix.                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                      │
│ sed -i '/for (auto \*U : IVUsers) {/,/}/ a\                                                                                  │
│   // Fix up PHI nodes in the exit block that use loop-invariant values.\                                                     │
│   for (BasicBlock *ExitBB : L->getExitBlocks()) {\                                                                           │
│     if (!VectorLoopExitBB->getTerminator()->isSuccessor(ExitBB))\                                                            │
│       continue;\                                                                                                             │
│     for (PHINode &PN : ExitBB->phis()) {\                                                                                    │
│       if (PN.getBasicBlockIndex(VectorLoopExitBB) != -1)\                                                                    │
│         continue;\                                                                                                           │
│       // The PHI is invalid. We need to add an entry for VectorLoopExitBB.\                                                  │
│       // The value must be a loop-invariant, so we can use any of the\                                                       │
│       // existing incoming values.\                                                                                          │
│       assert(PN.getNumIncomingValues() > 0 && "PHI has no incoming values?");\                                               │
│       Value *V = PN.getIncomingValue(0);\                                                                                    │
│       PN.addIncoming(V, VectorLoopExitBB);\                                                                                  │
│     }\                                                                                                                       │
│   }' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp                                                                         │
